TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Nature of Long-Term Unemployment: Predictability,                         Heterogeneity, and Selection
AU  - Mueller, Andreas I.
AU  - Spinnewijn, Johannes
Y1  - 2025/08/12
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/738045
DO  - 10.1086/738045
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3846
EP  - 3902
VL  - 133
IS  - 12
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper studies the predictability of long-term unemployment (LTU) using rich administrative data from Sweden. We establish substantial heterogeneity in LTU risk across individuals, accounting for both observed and unobserved heterogeneity using a wide range of observable predictors and multiple-spell outcomes, respectively. We apply our prediction algorithm to study the dynamics of job finding over the unemployment spell and the business cycle. Selection effects can explain most of the decline in average job finding over the unemployment spell but little of its cyclicality. We also find sizable heterogeneity in the profiles of job finding over the unemployment spell but not over the business cycle.
AB  - This paper studies the predictability of long-term unemployment (LTU) using rich administrative data from Sweden. We establish substantial heterogeneity in LTU risk across individuals, accounting for both observed and unobserved heterogeneity using a wide range of observable predictors and multiple-spell outcomes, respectively. We apply our prediction algorithm to study the dynamics of job finding over the unemployment spell and the business cycle. Selection effects can explain most of the decline in average job finding over the unemployment spell but little of its cyclicality. We also find sizable heterogeneity in the profiles of job finding over the unemployment spell but not over the business cycle.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/738045
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/738045
Y2  - 2026/04/24
