TY  - JOUR
T1  - Exorbitant Privilege Gained and Lost: Fiscal                         Implications
AU  - Chen, Zefeng
AU  - Jiang, Zhengyang
AU  - Lustig, Hanno
AU  - Van Nieuwerburgh, Stijn
AU  - Xiaolan, Mindy Z.
Y1  - 2025/08/20
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/738149
DO  - 10.1086/738149
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3713
EP  - 3761
VL  - 133
IS  - 12
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study three centuries of fiscal history. Dominant safe asset suppliers issue more debt than future primary surpluses can justify, even after accounting for seigniorage revenue from convenience yields. This pattern holds for the Dutch Republic (seventeenth to eighteenth centuries), the United Kingdom (eighteenth to nineteenth centuries), and the United States (twentieth to twenty-first centuries). When Dutch and UK fiscal fundamentals deteriorated, they lost their dominant position as the safe asset supplier, and their debt became fully backed by primary surpluses. Exorbitant privilege stems from issuing overpriced debt in the early stage, followed by bondholder losses and financial repression in the later stage.
AB  - We study three centuries of fiscal history. Dominant safe asset suppliers issue more debt than future primary surpluses can justify, even after accounting for seigniorage revenue from convenience yields. This pattern holds for the Dutch Republic (seventeenth to eighteenth centuries), the United Kingdom (eighteenth to nineteenth centuries), and the United States (twentieth to twenty-first centuries). When Dutch and UK fiscal fundamentals deteriorated, they lost their dominant position as the safe asset supplier, and their debt became fully backed by primary surpluses. Exorbitant privilege stems from issuing overpriced debt in the early stage, followed by bondholder losses and financial repression in the later stage.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/738149
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/738149
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Self-Fulfilling Debt Crises with Long Stagnations
AU  - Ayres, Joao
AU  - Navarro, Gaston
AU  - Nicolini, Juan Pablo
AU  - Teles, Pedro
Y1  - 2025/08/20
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/738143
DO  - 10.1086/738143
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 4050
EP  - 4101
VL  - 133
IS  - 12
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We assess the quantitative relevance of expectations-driven sovereign debt crises, focusing on the southern European crisis of the early 2010s and the Argentine default of 2001. The source of multiplicity is the one proposed by Calvo. Crucial for multiplicity is an output process characterized by long periods of either high growth or stagnation, which we estimate using data for these countries. Our analysis suggests that expectations-driven debt crises are quantitatively relevant but state dependent, as they occur only during periods of stagnation. Expectations and how they respond to policy are the major factors explaining default rates and credit spread differences between Spain and Argentina.
AB  - We assess the quantitative relevance of expectations-driven sovereign debt crises, focusing on the southern European crisis of the early 2010s and the Argentine default of 2001. The source of multiplicity is the one proposed by Calvo. Crucial for multiplicity is an output process characterized by long periods of either high growth or stagnation, which we estimate using data for these countries. Our analysis suggests that expectations-driven debt crises are quantitatively relevant but state dependent, as they occur only during periods of stagnation. Expectations and how they respond to policy are the major factors explaining default rates and credit spread differences between Spain and Argentina.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/738143
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/738143
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Distribution Regression with Sample Selection and UK Wage                         Decomposition
AU  - Chernozhukov, Victor
AU  - Fernández-Val, Iván
AU  - Luo, Siyi
Y1  - 2025/08/20
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/738148
DO  - 10.1086/738148
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3952
EP  - 3992
VL  - 133
IS  - 12
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We develop a distribution regression model under endogenous sample selection. This model is a semiparametric generalization of the Heckman selection model, which accommodates much richer patterns of heterogeneity in the effect of covariates and selection process and allows for departures from Gaussian errors while maintaining the same level of tractability. The model applies to continuous, discrete, and mixed outcomes. We provide identification, estimation, and inference methods and apply them to obtain wage decompositions in the United Kingdom. Here we decompose the difference between the male and female wage distributions into composition, wage structure, selection structure, and selection sorting effects.
AB  - We develop a distribution regression model under endogenous sample selection. This model is a semiparametric generalization of the Heckman selection model, which accommodates much richer patterns of heterogeneity in the effect of covariates and selection process and allows for departures from Gaussian errors while maintaining the same level of tractability. The model applies to continuous, discrete, and mixed outcomes. We provide identification, estimation, and inference methods and apply them to obtain wage decompositions in the United Kingdom. Here we decompose the difference between the male and female wage distributions into composition, wage structure, selection structure, and selection sorting effects.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/738148
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/738148
Y2  - 2026/04/24
