TY  - JOUR
T1  - Artificial Intelligence in the Knowledge Economy
AU  - Ide, Enrique
AU  - Talamàs, Eduard
Y1  - 2025/06/17
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/737233
DO  - 10.1086/737233
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3762
EP  - 3800
VL  - 133
IS  - 12
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Artificial intelligence (AI) can transform the knowledge economy by automating noncodifiable work. To analyze this transformation, we incorporate AI into an economy where humans form hierarchical organizations: less knowledgeable individuals become ?workers? doing routine work, while others become ?solvers? handling exceptions. We model AI as a technology that converts computational resources into ?AI agents? that operate autonomously (as coworkers and solvers/copilots) or nonautonomously (solely as copilots). Autonomous AI primarily benefits the most knowledgeable individuals; nonautonomous AI benefits the least knowledgeable. However, output is higher with autonomous AI. These findings reconcile contradictory empirical evidence and reveal trade-offs when regulating AI autonomy.
AB  - Artificial intelligence (AI) can transform the knowledge economy by automating noncodifiable work. To analyze this transformation, we incorporate AI into an economy where humans form hierarchical organizations: less knowledgeable individuals become ?workers? doing routine work, while others become ?solvers? handling exceptions. We model AI as a technology that converts computational resources into ?AI agents? that operate autonomously (as coworkers and solvers/copilots) or nonautonomously (solely as copilots). Autonomous AI primarily benefits the most knowledgeable individuals; nonautonomous AI benefits the least knowledgeable. However, output is higher with autonomous AI. These findings reconcile contradictory empirical evidence and reveal trade-offs when regulating AI autonomy.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/737233
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/737233
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Migration, Specialization, and Trade: Evidence from Brazil’s                         March to the West
AU  - Pellegrina, Heitor S.
AU  - Sotelo, Sebastian
Y1  - 2025/08/18
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/738147
DO  - 10.1086/738147
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3993
EP  - 4049
VL  - 133
IS  - 12
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study how migration shapes aggregate and regional comparative advantage, exploiting a large migration of farmers to Brazil?s West between 1950 and 2010. Migration allowed workers to sort according to their own comparative advantage, reallocating knowledge and raw labor to high-productivity regions. In a quantitative model, we find that migration cost reductions reshaped Brazil?s comparative advantage and contributed to its rise as a leading commodity exporter?accounting for 25% of the observed changes in specialization. Road expansions were key drivers of migration. Migration opportunities, moreover, account for a substantial share of the gains from trade.
AB  - We study how migration shapes aggregate and regional comparative advantage, exploiting a large migration of farmers to Brazil?s West between 1950 and 2010. Migration allowed workers to sort according to their own comparative advantage, reallocating knowledge and raw labor to high-productivity regions. In a quantitative model, we find that migration cost reductions reshaped Brazil?s comparative advantage and contributed to its rise as a leading commodity exporter?accounting for 25% of the observed changes in specialization. Road expansions were key drivers of migration. Migration opportunities, moreover, account for a substantial share of the gains from trade.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/738147
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/738147
Y2  - 2026/04/24
